ion). He also shows how Jewish Communists viewed, interacted, and celebrated with their Palestinian comrades. Using extensive archival and newspaper sources, Locker-Biletzki argues that Jewish-Israeli Communists created a unique, dissident subculture. Simultaneously negating and absorbing the culture of Socialist-Zionism and Israeli Republicanism—as well as Soviet and left-wing–European traditions—Jewish Communists forged an Israeli identity beyond the bounds of Zionism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and JudaismzIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunistszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolidayszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish communistszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Parties. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848087940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480879/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles